TITLE: Parsing with @babel/parser - Template Literal Tokenization
DESCRIPTION: This snippet shows the change in how template literals are tokenized in Babel 8. Babel 7 uses a single `template` token type, while Babel 8 introduces `templateNonTail` and `templateTail` to distinguish between non-tail and tail parts of the literal. Dependencies: `@babel/parser`.
SOURCE: https://github.com/babel/website/blob/main/docs/v8-migration-api.md#_snippet_71

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
import { parse } from "@babel/parser";

const { tokens } = parse("`head${x}middle${y}tail``", { tokens: true });
console.log(tokens); // print tokens
// Babel 7
// [
//  Token (`),
//  Token (template) { value: "head" }, Token (${),
//  Token (name) { value: "x" }, Token (}),
//  Token (template) { value: "middle" }, Token (${),
//  Token (name) { value: "y" }, Token (}),
//  Token (template) { value: "tail" }
//  Token (``)
// ]
// Babel 8
// [
//  Token (templateNonTail) { value: "head" },
//  Token (name) { value: "x" },
//  Token (templateNonTail) { value: "middle" },
//  Token (name) { value: "y" },
//  Token (templateTail) { value: "tail" }
// ]
```

